## .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

This code has several constructs that are broken or obsolete in modern .NET:

### Critical Pitfalls

| Issue | Impact |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed in .NET 5+ |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Obsolete, unreliable for waking `WaitOne` in .NET Core |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` | Race condition: multiple rapid `Enqueue` calls before `Reset()` → only one item processed, rest stuck |
| No cancellation model | No cooperative shutdown; relies on hard-kill APIs that no longer exist |
| Bare `while(true)` | No way to drain the queue gracefully on shutdown |

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _processTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _processTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();  // signal no more items

        // Wait for drain, then force-cancel if it takes too long
        using var timeoutCts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
        try
        {
            await (_processTask ?? Task.CompletedTask).WaitAsync(timeoutCts.Token);
        }
        catch (TimeoutException)
        {
            _cts?.Cancel();       // cooperative cancellation replaces Abort()
            await (_processTask ?? Task.CompletedTask).ConfigureAwait(false);
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) => Console.WriteLine(item);
}
```

### Key Changes Explained

1. **`Channel<T>` replaces `Queue` + `ManualResetEvent` + `lock`** — thread-safe, backpressure-aware, no manual synchronization, and fixes the race condition where items were silently dropped.

2. **`CancellationToken` replaces `Abort()`/`Interrupt()`** — the only supported shutdown mechanism in .NET 5+. Cooperative cancellation is safe and deterministic.

3. **`Task.Run` replaces `new Thread`** — uses the thread pool instead of dedicating an OS thread. For long-lived CPU-bound work, consider `Task.Factory.StartNew(..., TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning)`.

4. **Two-phase shutdown** — `Writer.Complete()` first drains the queue gracefully; `CancellationToken` is the fallback hard stop. This replaces the old "interrupt then abort" pattern.

5. **`IAsyncDisposable`** — ensures cleanup in `await using` blocks, idiomatic for .NET 8.

### If you need a synchronous API (drop-in replacement)

```csharp
public void Stop()
{
    StopAsync(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5))
        .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
}
```

Use this only at application boundaries — prefer `await StopAsync()` everywhere else to avoid deadlocks.
